# Day 64 – Task R-1: Assembling the Authorization Package | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## The Authorize Step Begins

Day 63 produced the final post-assessment POA&M — ten open items, one Moderate and nine Low, each with documented compensating controls, milestone schedules, and responsible owners. The Assess step is complete. Today begins the sixth step of the NIST RMF: Authorize.

The Authorize step has two tasks. Task R-1 — today — assembles the authorization package: the complete set of documents that the Authorizing Official will review to make the authorization decision. Task R-2 — Day 65 — is the AO's review, risk determination, and authorization decision itself.

The authorization package is not a new document — it is a structured assembly of work products that already exist, organized for the AO's review in a way that supports a defensible risk decision. The SSP, SAR, and POA&M have all been produced and iteratively refined over the past several weeks. The task today is ensuring they are internally consistent, that the executive summary accurately represents the risk posture, and that the package is organized so the AO can navigate it efficiently.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-37 Task R-1 requires the system owner and ISSO to compile the authorization package — at minimum: the SSP (including all supporting documentation), the SAR, and the POA&M. The package is submitted to the AO with sufficient supporting material that the AO can make an informed, documented, risk-based authorization decision without needing to request additional information.

Today I work through each component of the authorization package, verify internal consistency across documents, identify and resolve any cross-document discrepancies, produce the executive summary, and document the package index that tells the AO what is in the package and where to find specific information.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified authorization package assembly today is cross-document consistency — and why it matters more than any individual document being thorough.

Each document in the authorization package was produced at a different point in the process by different people working different tasks. The SSP was written and updated across Days 43 through 56. The SAR was produced by the external assessor. The POA&M has been updated incrementally since Day 50. The executive summary is being written today.

Any inconsistency across these documents creates a problem for the AO. If the SSP says backup retention is 90 days and the SAR says the assessor found a retention discrepancy corrected to 35 days that was subsequently fixed, the AO needs to be able to trace the full story — original documentation, finding, correction, current state. If the POA&M lists CP-2 as "partially implemented — draft exists" but the SAR assessor noted that "the draft scope is more limited than the POA&M implies," those characterizations need to be reconciled before the package goes to the AO. If the executive summary says "zero high-risk findings" and the SAR found three Moderate findings that were resolved pre-authorization, the executive summary needs to accurately represent the resolved findings rather than omitting them.

Cross-document consistency is how the AO knows the package reflects a coherent, honest picture of the system — not a best-case narrative assembled from selectively interpreted documents.

