### Component 4: Executive Summary

The executive summary is the first document the AO will read. It needs to be accurate, complete, and structured for an executive audience — conveying the essential risk picture without requiring the AO to read the full SSP, SAR, and POA&M to understand the system's security posture.

---

**EXECUTIVE SUMMARY — AUTHORIZATION PACKAGE**
**System:** MyClinic OpenMRS Electronic Health Record System (MCOPENMRS-001)
**Date:** [authorization package date]
**Prepared by:** Information Security Lead (ISSO)
**Submitted to:** MyClinic Executive Director (Authorizing Official)

---

**System Overview**

MyClinic OpenMRS is a cloud-hosted electronic health record system deployed on Amazon Web Services, supporting clinical operations including patient registration, encounter documentation, medication management, and laboratory result tracking. The system processes, stores, and transmits electronic protected health information for MyClinic's patient population. The system is categorized as HIGH impact across all three security objectives (confidentiality, integrity, and availability), reflecting the sensitivity of ePHI, the use of the system for real-time clinical decision support, and the absence of a fully tested paper-based downtime procedure.

**Assessment Summary**

The system underwent a full NIST SP 800-53 Rev 5 High baseline assessment conducted by [external firm name] between [start date] and [end date]. The assessment used NIST SP 800-53A examine, interview, and test methods across all control families. The assessor reviewed the System Security Plan, assessed AWS infrastructure using read-only console access, tested OpenMRS application controls in a production-equivalent test environment, and interviewed four MyClinic personnel.

The assessment identified seven findings: three Moderate severity and four Low severity. No High-severity findings were identified — the system's core security architecture (encryption, network controls, authentication, and audit logging) is implemented and operating effectively.

**Pre-Authorization Remediation**

All three Moderate findings were resolved before this authorization package was submitted:

The IAM administrator role included an unrestricted `iam:PassRole` permission creating a privilege escalation pathway. This was corrected by restricting the permission to two named roles required for operational functions. The assessor verified the remediation.

An undocumented service account created for a monitoring integration had console access enabled with no MFA enrollment. Console access was disabled, the account was added to the IAM inventory and quarterly review scope, and an automated EventBridge notification was implemented to alert the ISSO of any future IAM entity creation. The assessor verified the remediation.

The change management procedure did not list IAM entity creation as a required ISSO-notification change category — the root cause that allowed the service account gap to go undetected. The procedure was updated and the IT Administrator was briefed. The assessor verified the remediation.

Two Low findings were resolved as documentation updates (KMS key policy root account condition added to SSP; access review template root cause analysis). Four Low findings are tracked in the POA&M.

**Current Risk Posture**

Zero Moderate or High findings remain open. The system's residual risk is concentrated in one Moderate POA&M item (clinical downtime procedures — Item 001) and nine Low POA&M items. The clinical downtime procedures gap is the most operationally significant open item: while the system's technical recovery capability is tested and functional, clinical staff procedures for operating during an EHR outage are not fully documented or drilled. This gap affects patient care continuity during a downtime event more than the system's security posture.

**Assessor Authorization Recommendation**

The external assessor recommended authorization. The three conditions from the conditional authorization recommendation (remediate Moderate findings A-1, A-3, and A-7) have been satisfied. The assessor's updated SAR supports unconditional authorization with POA&M tracking of the four remaining Low findings and the CP-2 Moderate item.

**ISSO Recommendation**

The ISSO recommends Authorization to Operate with the following AO-level awareness items:

The clinical downtime procedures (POA&M Item 001) have a 90-day completion target. This is the highest-priority open item and carries a Moderate risk rating given the system's High-impact categorization and its role in real-time patient care. The AO may wish to establish a 90-day check-in to confirm this item is on track.

The quarterly POA&M status report process — first report due [date + 90 days] — will provide the AO with ongoing visibility into POA&M progress without requiring ad-hoc status requests.

