## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The authorization package navigation guide — the one-page AO question-to-section map — was something I added after thinking about the circumstances of the **2014 OPM breach** through a specific lens that does not usually come up: the authorization package documentation.

Post-breach investigation revealed that some OPM systems had operated for years on either expired ATOs or no ATOs at all. Congressional testimony suggested that authorization packages for some of these systems were, charitably, minimal — documentation that satisfied the form of the requirement without the substance.

One of the patterns that enables authorization to become a checkbox exercise rather than a genuine risk decision is authorization package complexity that overwhelms AOs who have limited time and broad responsibility. An AO reviewing twenty-plus systems annually cannot spend two hours reading each authorization package. If the package does not make the key risk information findable quickly, the AO either defers to the ISSO's recommendation without engaging the underlying evidence, or approves to clear a queue rather than to accept a specific, understood risk.

The navigation guide is a small but meaningful design choice for MyClinic's AO — the Executive Director who has clinical and administrative responsibilities beyond cybersecurity authorization. Making the key risk information findable in under ten minutes respects the AO's time while preserving the accountability that authorization is supposed to create. The AO should be able to read the executive summary (five minutes), review the POA&M summary table (two minutes), and ask one or two informed questions — and arrive at a genuine risk acceptance decision, not an administrative approval.

That is what authorization is supposed to be.

