## What I Am Still Thinking About

One question from today's package assembly: what is the right level of detail in the executive summary?

The executive summary I drafted today is about 600 words — long for an executive summary, but the system is High-impact and the AO needs substantive information. A shorter summary risks omitting material information that the AO needs to make a genuine risk decision. A longer summary risks becoming another document the AO skims rather than reads.

My instinct is that the right framework for executive summary length is: include every piece of information that, if omitted, could cause the AO to make a different authorization decision or ask a follow-up question. Include nothing else.

For this package, the material information is: what the system does, why it is High-impact, that no High or Moderate findings remain open, what the three resolved Moderate findings were and how they were fixed, what the one remaining Moderate POA&M item is (CP-2) and its 90-day timeline, and what ongoing visibility the AO will have through the quarterly POA&M report. Everything else is detail available in the package for the AO who wants to go deeper.

That framework produces a 500-700 word executive summary for a High-impact healthcare EHR. For a simpler system with fewer findings, the summary would be shorter. The length should follow the material information requirement, not a word count target.

